<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="294" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1396,1709]" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1396,1421]" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The new species is a twin species of 
<taxonomicName box="[699,829,1397,1420]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiensis">
<emphasis box="[699,829,1397,1420]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. apiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with easily recognisable external and genital features which are as follows: The forewing ground colour of 
<taxonomicName box="[768,982,1431,1456]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Maculonola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dolokmerangiri">
<emphasis box="[768,982,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. dolokmerangiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is somewhat paler with more brownish shine (
<taxonomicName box="[226,355,1469,1492]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiensis">
<emphasis box="[226,355,1469,1492]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. apiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more greyish); the forewing patches of the new species are more blurred, except the large one at the ventral margin, which is larger and more sharply defined than in 
<taxonomicName box="[946,1075,1505,1528]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiensis">
<emphasis box="[946,1075,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. apiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1396,1709]" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">
In the male genitalia, the new species (gen. fig. 
<number box="[764,794,1540,1564]" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" value="42.0">42</number>
) has, compared with 
<taxonomicName box="[1047,1179,1541,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiensis">
<emphasis box="[1047,1179,1541,1564]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. apiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(gen. fig. 
<number box="[1305,1336,1540,1564]" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" value="41.0">41</number>
), slighly narrower valva, fully truncate harpe (that of 
<taxonomicName box="[654,784,1577,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiensis">
<emphasis box="[654,784,1577,1600]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. apiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has short, pointed apical process arising at distal margin) and much longer basal costal process. The aedeagus of the two species are rather similar, but the short coecum penis is quadrangular in the new species, and rounded in 
<taxonomicName box="[791,920,1649,1672]" class="Insecta" family="Nolidae" genus="Meganola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="294" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apiensis">
<emphasis box="[791,920,1649,1672]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">M. apiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,1396,1709]" box="[199,400,1684,1709]" pageId="43" pageNumber="294">Female unknown.</paragraph>
